## Issue Tracking

Use `bd` (beads) for all issue tracking. Dependencies and parallelism are tracked natively:
- `bd ready` shows unblocked issues available to work on
- `bd dep add X Y` to declare Y blocks X
- `bd close <id>` to mark work done
- Always use `--json` flag when parsing output programmatically

## Migration Skills

The following skills are available for migration work:

- **module-triage**: Inventory the project and produce _triage.yaml
- **reference-packages**: Identify best existing packages as architecture blueprints
- **spec-extract**: Study source + test files, produce spec with citations to original code
- **spec-reconcile**: Cross-reference all specs, find gaps, reconcile triage
- **migration-implement**: Implement a module using spec citations as guide
- **xcuitest-verify**: Write and run XCUITest e2e tests from behavioral spec
- **progress-report**: Migration progress dashboard — run each morning

## Ralph Loops

Autonomous execution via `scripts/ralph.sh`. Pools:
- `general` — spec extraction (sonnet)
- `code-author` — implementation (opus)
- `test-author` — XCUITest writing (sonnet)

When closing a bead, use: `scripts/bd-done.sh <bead-id> -r "summary"`

## Project Layout

- **`./SecuroNet/`** — Legacy UIKit MVC/Coordinator code. Do NOT replicate patterns from here.
- **`./Packages/`** — New SwiftUI + MVVM Swift packages. All new code goes here.

## Reference Packages

When implementing a new module, study these packages FIRST to learn the project's architecture patterns. Read their Views, ViewModels, Services, and Tests before writing any code.

- `Packages/{PACKAGE_1}` — {DESCRIPTION: e.g., "login flow — shows ViewModel + View + navigation pattern"}
- `Packages/{PACKAGE_2}` — {DESCRIPTION: e.g., "dashboard — complex list with search/filter, data loading pattern"}
- `Packages/{PACKAGE_3}` — {DESCRIPTION: e.g., "networking — horizontal, shows service protocol pattern"}

These are the most architecturally representative packages in the project. Every new module should match their patterns for Views, ViewModels, dependency injection, navigation, and testing.

## Specs Directory

`specs/` contains module specifications with citations to source code.
- Read specs before implementing — they provide high-level understanding
- Follow `Source:` references to study original implementation details
- Respect `## Misplaced Logic` — do NOT reimplement, consume as a dependency
- Format: `specs/{group}/{module_name}.md`

## Build & Test

These are the exact commands for building and testing this project:

```bash
# Build (verify compilation)
xcodebuild build -scheme {SCHEME} -destination 'generic/platform=iOS Simulator'

# Unit tests
xcodebuild test -scheme {SCHEME} -destination 'platform=iOS Simulator,name={SIMULATOR}'

# UI tests (XCUITest)
xcodebuild test -scheme {UI_TEST_SCHEME} -destination 'platform=iOS Simulator,name={SIMULATOR}'
```

- Scheme: `{SCHEME}`
- UI Test Scheme: `{UI_TEST_SCHEME}`
- Simulator: `{SIMULATOR}` (e.g., `iPhone 16`)
- Unit test target: `{TEST_TARGET}`
- UI test target: `{UI_TEST_TARGET}`
